Kowloon's Jade Magistracy holds the Great Oasis in high institutional regard as the founding site of the administrative water-arbitration tradition that influenced Kowloon's own covenant law. House Vao's grain-arbitration courts descend from the same intellectual tradition as the High Water Court — scarce shared resources require neutral arbitration rather than competitive extraction. The oasis's collapse into three-faction conflict is cited in Kowloon's covenant law texts as the canonical failure case: what happens when pragmatists, legalists, and ritualists cannot maintain coalition governance of a shared resource. Kowloon has no direct presence at the oasis but maintains intelligence through desert caravan intermediaries.

