Mafdet's institutional relationship to the Great Oasis is downstream and archival. The Littoral Branch of Measure Script that became Mafdet's Ledger House notation system developed from the same Keeper administrative tradition that built the Cistern Ring and Waystone Circle. The oasis's Charter of Passage — asserting unrestricted water access for any properly documented traveler — has a direct analog in Mafdet's harbor right-of-entry law. Both laws were designed to maintain open-access infrastructure against political pressure to restrict it. Mafdet's Ledger Houses attest desert-origin cargo including goods that passed through the oasis corridor; access disruption appears in Mafdet records as "desert corridor delay" on manifests.

