Khephari geological analysis identifies the underground spring system as a fracture-limestone aquifer dependent on distant recharge zones that the Iseth Reach river once fed directly. The river's drying severed the recharge connection; the springs did not immediately fail because the aquifer had stored water under pressure, but long-term drawdown was inevitable once recharge stopped. The Ninth Meridian Rite's failure did not cause the springs to diminish — it accelerated a process already underway. The cistern ring was correctly engineered for flood regulation, not drought survival, because the original Keeper-period engineers were building for a world where the Iseth Reach still functioned. The third spring's failure approximately fifty years ago is consistent with continued aquifer pressure reduction; the remaining two springs have a calculable remaining useful lifespan under current draw rates that the Spring Wardens have not formally assessed.
